# Always Work In A Git Worktree

To allow multiple agents to work on this repo simultaneously without stepping on each other (branch switches, file changes, dirty state), every task MUST be performed in a dedicated git worktree on its own branch.

## Workflow

1. Before making any code changes, check whether you are already in a worktree dedicated to this task:

```bash
git rev-parse --show-toplevel
git worktree list
```

2. If you are still in the main checkout (or sharing a worktree with another task), create a new one off the latest `main` and switch into it:

```bash
# from the main repo root
git fetch origin
git worktree add -b feat/<feature_name> ../duffy-ai-feat-<feature_name> origin/main --no-track
cd ../duffy-ai-feat-<feature_name>
```

Use `feat/<feature_name>` for features and `fix/<fix_name>` for fixes (matches the project branch convention).

The `--no-track` flag is REQUIRED. Without it, the new branch inherits `origin/main` as its upstream, and a later `git push` (or Cursor's "Sync") will push the branch's commits straight to `origin/main`, bypassing PR review. With `--no-track`, the branch has no upstream until the first `git push`, which then creates a same-named remote branch (`origin/feat/<feature_name>`).

3. Do ALL editing, testing, and committing inside that worktree directory. Never `git checkout <other-branch>` in a worktree another agent might be using.

4. Make the worktree self-contained for package installs. If `node_modules` is a symlink to the main checkout's `node_modules` (common pattern when bootstrapping a worktree fast), `pnpm add` and friends will fail with `ERR_PNPM_UNEXPECTED_VIRTUAL_STORE` because pnpm rejects a shared virtual store. BEFORE the first install, break the symlink and give the worktree its own install:

```bash
# inside the worktree
[ -L node_modules ] && rm node_modules
pnpm install
```

Never "unblock" a failing `pnpm add` / `pnpm install` / `drizzle-kit` / etc. by running it in the main checkout. That silently mutates files on `main` and leaks them into whatever commit you make from main next.

5. Before every mutating command (install, migration, codegen, file edit via terminal tools, commit), verify you're inside the worktree:

```bash
git rev-parse --show-toplevel   # MUST print the worktree path, not the main checkout
git branch --show-current       # MUST print the feature/fix branch, not main
```

6. Commit ONLY via terminals/tools rooted in the worktree directory. Do not commit via an IDE UI that is opened on the main checkout folder — its Source Control panel is bound to that folder's git index and will commit any modified files there to whatever branch that folder is on (usually `main`). Either:
   - commit from a terminal whose cwd is the worktree, OR
   - open the worktree in its own IDE window (`File > Open Folder` → the worktree path) and commit from there.

7. When the task is done and merged, clean up:

```bash
# from the main repo root
git worktree remove ../duffy-ai-feat-<feature_name>
git branch -d feat/<feature_name>   # only if fully merged
```

## Rules

- One worktree per task/branch. Do not reuse a worktree for an unrelated task.
- Never run `git checkout <branch>` to switch branches in-place — create a new worktree instead.
- Place worktrees as siblings of the main repo (e.g. `../duffy-ai-<slug>`), never nested inside it.
- If a worktree for the target branch already exists, `cd` into it instead of creating a duplicate.
- If you cannot create a worktree (e.g. uncommitted changes block it), stop and report the blocker rather than working in the shared checkout.
- If ANY command fails because of the environment in the worktree (pnpm store, drizzle-kit resolution, missing node_modules, etc.), fix it inside the worktree — never retry the command from the main checkout to "unblock" yourself. Installing or generating in the main checkout is the #1 way feature work leaks onto `main`.
- Before finishing a feature, sanity-check that `main` didn't drift. From the main checkout: `git log origin/main..main --oneline` MUST be empty (no accidental commits on main) and `git status --short` MUST be clean. If it isn't, those changes belong on the feature branch, not `main` — cherry-pick them over and reset main.

## Quick Reference

```bash
git worktree list                                              # see all active worktrees
git worktree add -b <branch> <path> origin/main --no-track     # create new worktree + branch (no main upstream!)
git worktree remove <path>                                     # clean up when done
git worktree prune                                             # drop stale entries
```
